 columns. The queried samples should be labelled as follows: sample_additional information (e.g. stomach_adult patient 1). To get a meaningful prediction of the queried samples, the tissue\\/cell type of interest must be represented in the training set.<\\/li><li>Press the submit button and check your mailbox for the results.<\\/li><\\/ol><h4>2.2. Web app using \\u201cflexible\\u201d training sets<\\/h4><p>We are currently working on the Web App to allow the use of flexible training sets.<\\/p>\",\"reference_alias\":\"how-to-use\",\"id\":\"3\",\"status\":\"published\",\"created_by\":\"1\",\"created_on\":\"2019-08-06 13:27:47\",\"title\":\"How to use\",\"github_link\":false}','{\"status\":\"published\",\"github_link\":false,\"title\":\"How to use\",\"reference_alias\":\"how-to-use\",\"content\":\"<h3>1. Provided \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets<\\/h3><p>KeyGenes has been developed and tested using NGS-derived human fetal transcriptional datasets as both training and test sets (Roost et al., 2015). The datasets used were expanded with available datasets on human adult tissues\\/organs (Cnop et al., 2014; Fagerberg et al., 2014; Illumina Body Map 2.0).<\\/p><p>It is worth mentioning, that NGS-derived data of more human adult organs\\/tissues are available (Fagerberg et al., 2014; Illumina Bodymap 2.0; Epigenomic Roadmap; ENCODE) and could be incorporated as the datasets to be used as training sets are flexible and expandable. We provide seven basic \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets, which are supposed to give users a headstart to assign both identity and developmental stages to their differentiated cells (test set). How to create and use a \\u201cflexible\\u201d training set is described in section 2.<\\/p><h5>1. 1 Basic training set<\\/h5><p>KeyGenes has been developed and tested using NGS-derived human fetal transcriptional datasets as both training and test sets (Roost et al., 2015). The datasets used were expanded with available datasets on human adult tissues\\/o