g et al., 2014; Illumina Bodymap 2.0; Epigenomic Roadmap; ENCODE) and could be incorporated as the datasets to be used as training sets are flexible and expandable. We provide seven basic \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets, which are supposed to give users a headstart to assign both identity and developmental stages to their differentiated cells (test set). How to create and use a \\u201cflexible\\u201d training set is described in section 2.<\\/p><h3>2. Web App<\\/h3><h5>2.1. Web app using the provided \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets<\\/h5><p>The web app allows a prediction of NGS-derived data based on one of the \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets described above in section 1.<\\/p><p>To run the KeyGenes Web App, follow the steps below:<\\/p><ol><li>Fill in your email address in the first field, so you will get the results in your mailbox.<\\/li><li>Choose the \\u201cfixed\\u201d training set of interest from the dropdown menu.<\\/li><li>Upload the test set containing the raw reads. The provided training sets are based on Ensembl Gene IDs. Therefore, the test set must be in a specific tab-separated text file with genes (Ensembl Gene IDs, no duplicates) as rows and the queried samples as columns. The queried samples should be labelled as follows: sample_additional information (e.g. stomach_adult patient 1). To get a meaningful prediction of the queried samples, the tissue\\/cell type of interest must be represented in the training set.<\\/li><li>Press the submit button and check your mailbox for the results.<\\/li><\\/ol><h4>2.2. Web app using \\u201cflexible\\u201d training sets<\\/h4><p>We are currently working on the Web App to allow the use of flexible training sets.<\\/p>\"}',NULL,NULL,NULL),(564,584,'pages','1','{\"content\":\"<p><strong style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">KeyGenes is an algorithm to predict the identity<\\/strong><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">and determines identity scores of queried samples (test set) to a provided group of samples